			<font color="black">On:&nbsp;05/11/1999 1:29:17 AM&nbsp;&nbsp;
			(<font color="blue"><B>List by:</font> <a href="http://www.everlore.com/magic/magic.asp?ID=113&mode=details&spname=Minor+Illusion&pg=1&sortby=1">Front</a><font color="black">/</font><a href="http://www.everlore.com/magic/magic.asp?ID=113&mode=details&spname=Minor+Illusion&pg=1&sortby=2">Back</a></B></a>)
			
			</font></b></font>
	
		</td>
		
	
	</tr>
	<tr>
		
			<td bgcolor="#DEDACB">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				Minor Illusion is good for meditating without interruption.  Most mobs won't notice you while you are transformed.  Exceptions are skeletons and other undead.<BR>
<BR>
This will not allow you to escape from combat.  If you are not already targeted by a mob, this will prevent the mob from attacking in the first place.<BR>
<BR>
While transformed you can cast spells, attack, and turn, but you cannot move forward or back.
				</font>
			</td>

	</tr>
	
	<tr>
		
			<td bgcolor="#D6D1BE">	
		
	
			</font>
			<font face="Verdana" size="1"><b>
			<font color="black">--Submited by:&nbsp;
			<a href="mailto:wnmoon@bellsouh.net">Mendel the Malodorous</a></font> 
			<font color="black">On:&nbsp;05/20/1999 12:52:17 PM&nbsp;&nbsp;
			</font></b></font>
	
		</td>
		
	
	</tr>
	<tr>
		
			<td bgcolor="#DEDACB">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				For the starting enchanter, the Minor Illusion spell should be used to avoid the notice of more dangerous creatures, e.g., rabid grizzlies, griffins, and other advesaries.  Note that while the enchanter may cast spells from this form, he may not move or defend himself.  The act of casting spells, especially offensive spells, will get the attention of many creatures, effectively disrupting the illusion.<BR>
<BR>
Also fun at parties.<BR>

				</font>
			</td>

	</tr>
	
